Paragraph:Item.Paragraph:Text: The patient is a 34 year old female who has been unable to achieve a satisfactory abdominal contour following pregnancy. She now presents for abdominoplasty for cosmetic purposes.

The patient was marked preoperatively in the standing position to indicate the abdominal midline, the planned incision, and any areas for liposuction. The markings and operative plan were reviewed and confirmed with the patient.Audio01

The patient was then taken to the OR where she was placed on the table in the supine position. SCD stockings were placed and activated prior to induction of GEA. Following induction of GEA, local anesthetic was infiltrated into the planned incision lines. The patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile fashion.

Puncture incisions were made and tumescent fluid was infiltrated into the planned zones of liposuction. While vasoconstriction was occurring, the umbilicus was grasped with two single hooks and was circumscribed around its perimeter. Dissection was then conducted along the umbilical stalk until the level of the abdominal wall was reached.Audio02

Liposuction was performed utilizing first a 4.0-mm Mercedes cannula with the PAL system. This was used for the deep layer of fat. This was followed by use of a 4.0-mm triple port cannula for final contouring and feathering. Liposuctioning was continued on each side, until the desired contour was reached. It was brought as far posteriorly as could be achieved with the patient remaining in the supine position. The aspirate remained non-bloody throughout the procedure.

Attention was then redirected to the abdomen. The transverse abdominoplasty incision was created and dissection was conducted squarely down to the level of the abdominal wall fascia. A prefascial plane of dissection was maintained using Bovie electrocautery, leaving a small quantity of fat on the abdominal wall. This was brought up to the level of the umbilicus, leaving the stalk in place and then brought from this level cephalad all the way up to the costal margin and the xiphoid process. Meticulous hemostasis was maintained throughout the procedure.

The abdominal wall was inspected and a midline diastasis was identified. The medial borders of the rectus muscle were then marked for plication. A suture of 0-loop Nylon was started at the xiphoid and extended down to the umbilicus. This was followed by a second suture from the umbilicus to the pubic bone. The zone of plication was infiltrated with 1/4 % Marcaine with epinepherine.

The patient was then placed into a flexed position on the OR table. The amount of skin redundancy was determined and marked. That planned incision was then infiltrated with local anesthetic. The planned location of the umbilicus at the superior iliac crest was also marked and infiltrated with local.

The redundant tissue was excised and hemostasis was obtained. A series of progressive tension sutures of 0-Vicryl was placed extending from Scarpa's fascia down to the midline. Scarpa's fascia was reapproximated with interrupted sutures of 0-Vicryl. The skin was reapproximated with a running subcuticular suture of 2-0 Prolene.
The umbilicus was brought out through an omega shaped incision and inset in two layers with buried dermal sutures of 4-0 Monocryl, followed by a simple running suture of 5-0 fast absorbing gut.
The incisions were then dressed with 1/2 inch Proxy strips, gauze 4x4's, Xeroform gauze over the umbilicus, and ABD pads over the liposuction incisions. An abdominal binder was applied.
The patient tolerated the procedure well and there were no operative complications. She was extubated and transported to the Recovery Room in stable condition.
